00:03:26.710 --> 00:03:32.070
mainstream clinical psychologists tend to approach psychosis?

55
00:03:32.399 --> 00:03:36.970
Yeah, so, well, basically, um, as a psychoanalyst, I

56
00:03:36.970 --> 00:03:40.309
see it as follows. Um, THE way I described

57
00:03:40.309 --> 00:03:44.750
it provides us with the viewpoint of an outsider.

58
00:03:45.149 --> 00:03:47.979
This is how it looks for people, um, but

59
00:03:47.979 --> 00:03:50.869
as a psychoanalyst, I'm, I'm, I'm interested in the

60
00:03:50.869 --> 00:03:52.910
question, yeah, but what is it that brings it

61
00:03:52.910 --> 00:03:57.009
about such an experience? Uh, THIS is not something,

62
00:03:57.559 --> 00:04:00.389
uh, random. This is not just noise in the

63
00:04:00.389 --> 00:04:03.675
mind. This is not. Not just a brain entering

64
00:04:03.675 --> 00:04:06.595
in a most chaotic state. For me it's the

65
00:04:06.595 --> 00:04:09.214
question of a human being, a human being that

66
00:04:09.475 --> 00:04:13.315
obviously has been challenged to such a degree that

