00:10:18.039 --> 00:10:20.440
attend to, like, that's also the point where, for

167
00:10:20.440 --> 00:10:24.710
example, a psychoanalyst could enter the scene. Uh, TO,

168
00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.840
to try to speak with people about what they

169
00:10:27.840 --> 00:10:31.349
experience and what is destabilizing them. So, for me,

170
00:10:31.359 --> 00:10:34.840
it's not like a categorical distinction between or you

171
00:10:34.840 --> 00:10:38.640
have a clinical problem or you don't. Um, OF

172
00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:41.880
course, as human beings, we tend to categorize and

173
00:10:41.880 --> 00:10:44.640
because that's what makes it a bit more easy

174
00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:47.799
for us, but actually, I, I see it as

175
00:10:47.799 --> 00:10:48.599
a continuum.

176
00:10:48.960 --> 00:10:52.000
Mhm. So let me ask you this, and please

177
00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.520
let me know if you think that this is

178
00:10:54.520 --> 00:11:02.190
something worth considering when evaluating whether someone Um, I

179
00:11:02.190 --> 00:11:06.469
mean, whether something that someone experiences should be classified

180
00:11:06.469 --> 00:11:09.390
as a mental disorder or not. So, uh, do

181
00:11:09.390 --> 00:11:13.429
you think that perhaps there would be instances, and

